It's also brought up near the end that, oh, we think about five million years back some advanced aliens terraformed a bunch of planets in an area a couple hundred light-years across centered on Earth and stocked them with genetically uplifted sapients, for whatever inscrutable ayylmao reason. This is never examined or explored any further.

I wanted to see more of the foxes and their world. I wanted to see how a species of obligate carnivores that doesn't do large-scale agriculture and is still figuring out animal husbandry produces enough food to support the population in their cities. I wanted to see soft fuzzy fox bellies getting rubbed and fluffy fox tails getting stroked by the human guy, but no.

They are described as just now figuring out how to mass-produce transistors after recent advances in solid state physics. How did people without lots of data processing power to throw at things like sequencing genomes manage to create a genetically engineered plague virus from scratch? I know people IRL who work in bioinformatics. If they can't set up a server and install their custom Python tools to search for patterns in genomic data, if you were to tell them they have to do what they do with blackboards and notebooks and fountain pens, like it's 1924 instead of 2024, they'd look at you like you were crazy.

The fox people, we are explicitly told, are really, really good at chemistry, but there are limits to what a flesh-and-blood brain can do, even if you make them a species of IQ-200 autistic supergeniuses, which they clearly aren't. In fact they're aliens, the last time they and humanity shared a common ancestor was forty or fifty million years back, so why does their society feel like Truman-era America with flying saucers? The alienness is limited to speaking a different language plus little things like the adult females having an estrus cycle, and to it being normal for them to have a craving for raw eggs, which they can somehow indulge regularly without having domesticated chickens. I get that they're obligate carnivores and maybe not inclined to gardening, but food comes from somewhere, ya know?

tl;dr I wanted more, and I wanted a different direction. Of course I am not being charged to read it, so I can't complain too much.
